# MCP Tool Patterns

## Three-Layer Architecture

Every data source must be split across exactly three layers:

```
core/<source>_client.py   ← HTTP sessions, auth, caching, connection management
tools/<source>_tools.py   ← Business logic, data parsing, derived signals
server/app.py             ← @mcp.tool() wrappers with docstrings Claude reads
```

### core/ — Client & Session Management

Owns everything below the business logic: auth tokens, HTTP sessions, SSL config,
instrument caches, retry logic. Tools call into core; core never calls tools.

```python
# ✅ GOOD — core/nse_client.py
def nse_fetch(url: str) -> dict | list:
    session = requests.Session()
    session.get("https://www.nseindia.com", ...)  # cookie priming
    return session.get(url, ...).json()

# ❌ BAD — HTTP session inside tools/nse_tools.py
def get_fii_dii_activity():
    session = requests.Session()  # belongs in core/, not here
    session.get("https://www.nseindia.com", ...)
```

Each new data source layer gets its own `core/<name>_client.py`:
- `core/kite_client.py`   → Zerodha Kite Connect (Layer 1)
- `core/nse_client.py`    → NSE public API session (Layer 2)
- `core/macro_client.py`  → yfinance (Layer 4) — global indices, commodities, forex, yields

### tools/ — Business Logic

Plain functions only — no MCP imports, no HTTP sessions, no auth.
The `@mcp.tool()` decorator lives in `server/app.py`, not in `tools/`.

```python
# ✅ GOOD — tools/kite_tools.py
from core.kite_client import get_kite

def get_quote(symbol: str) -> dict:
    kite = get_kite()        # delegates session/auth to core/
    ...
    return {"ltp": ..., "change": ...}

# ❌ BAD — don't import mcp in tool files; @mcp.tool() belongs in server/app.py
from mcp.server.fastmcp import FastMCP
@mcp.tool()
def get_quote(...): ...
```

## Tool Registration (server/app.py)

Always wrap with a docstring — Claude reads it to decide when to call the tool.

```python
# ✅ GOOD
@mcp.tool()
def quote(symbol: str) -> dict:
    """
    Get a live quote for any NSE/BSE stock or index.
    Use when user asks about current price, today's change, or session P&L.
    Examples: quote("RELIANCE"), quote("NIFTY 50")
    """
    return get_quote(symbol)
```

## Error Handling

Tools must return a dict with `"error"` key on failure — never raise unhandled exceptions.

```python
# ✅ GOOD
try:
    raw = kite.quote([instrument])
except Exception as e:
    return {"error": str(e), "symbol": symbol}

# ❌ BAD — crashes the MCP server
raw = kite.quote([instrument])  # unhandled exception
```

## Return Types

Always return `dict` or `list[dict]`. Include an `"as_of"` timestamp for any live data.
